## The Recall Rundown
This year has already seen 314 recall incidents, with 87 classified as Class I--the most severe category involving high risk of adverse health effects or death. This April alone, recalls have reached 71, revealing persistent quality control issues.

### A Repeat Offender Spotlight
Moonlight Packing Corporation and Albertsons Companies LLC remain notorious with double-digit recalls, all Class I. Such patterns indicate systemic lapses, not isolated incidents. With scores of 96 and 94 respectively, these companies have earned failing grades.

### Recent Scandals
From undeclared allergens to undeclared prescription drugs, recent recalls paint a grim picture. Zarlengo Italian Ice, for instance, has multiple products removed due to incomplete allergen declarations, endangering those with soy allergies. Even more concerning, products like "Boner Bears Honey Male Enhancement" included undeclared sildenafil--posing significant risks to unsuspecting consumers. A pinnacle of negligence is seen in F&amp;S Fresh Foods' sandwich recall, where visible sesame wasn't declared on the allergen label.

### Category Breakdown
Food safety lapses were most common in 'Allergens' (178 incidents this year), followed by 'Listeria' (113) and 'Salmonella' (104). Mislabeling incidents, while fewer, can have heightened consequences as seen in this month's allergy-related recalls.

### Final Thoughts
Companies must up their game to prevent such hazards to public health. The cost of neglecting safety standards is immeasurable--both in human and reputational terms.
